com.tsgrp.migration.node

Interface MigrationNode

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    BasicMigrationNode

    public interface MigrationNode
    Ah, the Migration Node...the heart and soul of OpenMigrate. From its inception in the Source from a lowly Queue Item and its expansion by the Source into a full-fledged node; then through the mapping layer as it goes through sometimes awkward changes; to the Target where it is persisted to some distant data store; it finally arrives at the LogWriter which records its journey for posterity.

    A Migration Node is comprised of the following elements:

    • A collection of attributes, either single-value or repeating, stored as a Map of NodeAttributes, sorted. Instead of storing Node values in instance variables, practically everything is stored as an attribute (so that components can act on all values, custom and built-in, via a common syntax).
    • Some of those attributes are RESERVED and cannot be removed.
      • Reserved attributes all begin with "om_".
      • Some, but not all, reserved attributes have dedicated getters and setters (e.g., getContentType()).
    • A Map of Associations (keyed and sorted by association type), which are ordered Lists of Nodes related to this Node in some form.
    • Optional associations versions, renditions and children.
    • A node ID (typically the same as the originating Queue Item ID).
    • The ID of the Queue from which this Node was created.
    • A list of IDs created by the Target from this Node; this starts out empty, of course, and the Target should populate this as it creates items.
    • Content.

    Most implementations will use BasicMigrationNode as their concrete class; but each MigrationSource can override that if it chooses and use a more specific extenstion of it.
